replies.bodyText:
I was curious and suspected that a non-contended read-only CHM might be very similar to plain HM because non-contended volatile read on x86 is as fast as a non-volatile read:
Benchmark     Mode  Cnt   Score   Error  Units
ChmBench.chm  avgt   10  21,687 ± 0,122  ns/op
ChmBench.hm   avgt   10  22,610 ± 0,163  ns/op

source:
@BenchmarkMode(Mode.AverageTime)
@OutputTimeUnit(TimeUnit.NANOSECONDS)
@State(Scope.Thread)
@Fork(value = 1, warmups = 1)
@Warmup(iterations = 10)
@Measurement(iterations = 10)
public class ChmBench {

    private final Map<String, Integer> chm = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
    private final Map<String, Integer> hm = new HashMap<>();

    {
        chm.put("1", 1);
        chm.put("2", 2);
        chm.put("3", 3);

        hm.putAll(chm);
    }

    @Benchmark
    public void chm() {
        chm.get("3");
        chm.get("1");
        chm.get("2");
    }

    @Benchmark
    public void hm() {
        hm.get("3");
        hm.get("1");
        hm.get("2");
    }
}
Maybe another CPU will be different, I don't know. I used JDK 1.8.
